A097001.name: A062402(x)=sigma(phi[x]) function is iterated; initial value=2^n; a(n)=largest term of trajectory.

A097002.name: A062402(x)=sigma(phi[x]) function is iterated; initial value=2^n; a(n)=smallest term of trajectory.

A097003.name: Function A062402[x]=phi[sigma[x]] is iterated. a(n) is the number of distinct terms arising in the trajectory of 2^n; a(n)=t(n)+c(n)=t+c, where t is the number of transient terms, c is the number of recurrent terms [in the terminal cycle].

A097004.name: Function A062402(x)=phi(sigma(x)) is iterated. Starting with 2^n, the n-th power of 2, a(n) is the count of distinct terms arising in trajectory; a(n)=t(n)+c(n)=t+c, where t is the number of transient terms, c is the number of recurrent terms [in the terminal cycle].

A097005.name: A062401(x) is iterated. Initial value = n!. a(n) is the path-length of trajectory = count of transients and recurrent terms, i.e., all distinct states arising in trajectory.

A097006.name: Consider the function f(x)=sigma(phi(x))=A062402(x) iterated with initial value n!; a(n) is the path-length of trajectory.

A097007.name: a(n) = index of first appearance of n in A096859.

A097008.name: a(n) = index of first appearance of n in A096862.

A097010.name: Numbers n such that zero is eventually reached when the map x -> A034460(x) is iterated, starting from x = n.

A097013.name: Smallest x such that sigma(x) mod 30 = n.

A097014.name: Smallest x such that sigma(x) mod 210 = n.

A097015.name: Smallest x such that Mod[sigma[x], A002110(n)]=A002110(n)-1.

A097016.name: a(n)=x is the first term in chain of consecutive integers, for all of which the value of sigma[x] is divisible by 6.

A097018.name: a(n) is the least number such that sigma(a(n)) is divisible by the n-th prime.

A097020.name: Initial terms of chains consisting of four consecutive integers, for none of which is the value of sigma-function divisible by six.

A097021.name: Initial terms of chains consisting of five consecutive integers, for neither of which the value of sigma-function is divisible by six.

A097023.name: Numbers n such that the sum of the divisors of 2*n^2 is a square.

A097024.name: Numbers in the 5-cycle-attractor if the function f(x)=A063919(x) is iterated; f(x) is the sum of unitary proper divisors.

A097025.name: Numbers n such that both sigma(n) and sigma(sigma(n)) are odd numbers.

A097026.name: Function f(x) = phi(x) + floor(x/2) is iterated, starting at x=n; a(n) is the length of terminal cycle (or 0 if no finite cycle exists).
formula: For n=2^j: a(2^j)=1, powers of 2 are fixed points.

A097027.name: Function f(x) = phi(x) + floor(x/2) is iterated; a(n) is the length of transient if the iteration was initiated at n.

A097028.name: Function f(x) = EulerPhi(x) + floor(x/2) is iterated; a(n) is the length of transient part and terminal cycle if the iteration was initiated at n. So a(n) is the number of distinct terms arising during iteration.

A097029.name: Fixed points when the function f(x) = EulerPhi(x) + floor(x/2) is iterated, i.e., solutions to f(x) = x.

A097030.name: Numbers in the cycle-attractors of length=14 if the function f(x)=A063919(x) is iterated; f(x) is the sum of unitary proper divisors.

A097031.name: Length of terminal cycle if unitary-proper-divisor-sum function f(x) = A063919(x) is iterated and the initial value is n.

A097032.name: Total length of transient and terminal cycle if unitary-proper-divisor-sum function f(x) = A034460(x) is iterated and the initial value is n. Number of distinct terms in iteration list, including also the terminal 0 in the count if the iteration doesn't end in a cycle.

A097033.name: Number of transient terms before either 0 or a finite cycle is reached when unitary-proper-divisor-sum-function f(x) = A034460(x) is iterated and the initial value is n.

A097034.name: Initial values for iteration of A063919(x) function such that iteration ends in the 14-cycle, i.e., in A097030.

A097035.name: Initial values for iteration of A063919(x) function such that iteration ends in the 5-cycle, i.e., in A097024.

A097036.name: Initial values for iteration of A063919[x] function such that iteration ends in a 3-cycle.

A097037.name: Initial values for iteration of A063919(x) function such that iteration ends in a 2-cycle, i.e., "attracted" by unitary amicable numbers, A063991.

A097039.name: a(n) = Sum_{i=0..n} i*L(i), where L = A000032.

A097040.name: a(n) = 2*sum(C(n,2k+1)*F(2k), k=0..floor((n-1)/2)), where F(n) are Fibonacci numbers A000045.

A097042.name: G.f. = (1 + 4 * g.f. for A096661)/(1 + 2 Sum_{m>=1} (-1)^m*q^(m^2)).
formula: Conjectural g.f.: 1 + 2*Sum_{n >= 1} q^(n*(n+1)/2)/( (1 + q^n) * Product_{k = 1..n} 1 - q^k ). - _Peter Bala_, Feb 19 2021

A097043.name: a(n) = n - a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1; a(1) = 1.
formula: a(1)=1; a(n) = n - a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1.

A097044.name: a(n) = n + a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1; a(1) = 1.
formula: a(1)=1; a(n) = n + a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1.

A097045.name: a(n) = a(n-1) - a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1; a(1) = 1.
formula: a(1)=1; a(n) = a(n-1) - a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1.

A097046.name: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1; a(1) = 1.
formula: a(1)=1; a(n) = a(n-1) + a(floor(sqrt(n))) for n > 1.

A097047.name: Decimal expansion of 1/(2*sqrt(3)) - Pi/36 + log(2 + sqrt(3))/3.

A097048.name: a(n) = least denominator Y of the proper fractions X/Y which need n or more terms as an Egyptian fraction.

A097049.name: a(n) = least numerator X of the proper fractions X/A097048(n) which need n or more terms as an Egyptian fraction.

A097051.name: a(n) = floor(n/a(floor(n/2))); a(1) = 1.
formula: If floor(log_2(n))=2k+1, then a(n) = floor(n/2^k). If floor(log_2(n))=2k, then a(n) = 2^k.

A097052.name: First occurrence of n in A096036 or 0 if n does not appear.

A097053.name: First occurrence of n in A097051.

A097055.name: Numbers n such that the interval n^2 < x < (n+1)^2 contains at least one nonsquare perfect power A097054.
formula: a(n) ~ n^(3/2). - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Aug 28 2016

A097056.name: Numbers n such that the interval n^2 < x < (n+1)^2 contains two or more distinct nonsquare perfect powers A097054.

A097057.name: Number of integer solutions to a^2 + b^2 + 2*c^2 + 2*d^2 = n.
formula: Euler transform of period 8 sequence [4, -2, 4, -8, 4, -2, 4, -4, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 17 2004
Multiplicative with a(n) = 4*b(n), b(2) = 2, b(2^e) = 6 if e > 1, b(p^e) = (p^(e+1) - 1) / (p - 1) if p > 2. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 17 2004
Expansion of (eta(q^2) * eta(q^4))^6 / (eta(q) * eta(q^8))^4 in powers of q.
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (8 t)) = 8 (t/i)^2 f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t). - _Michael Somos_, Jul 05 2011

A097058.name: Numbers of the form p^2 + 2^p for p prime.

A097059.name: Numbers of the form p^3 + 3^p for p prime.

A097060.name: Revrepfigits (reverse replicating Fibonacci-like digits): Numbers n such that their reversal occurs in a sequence generated by starting with the n digits of a number and then continuing the sequence with a number that is the sum of the previous n terms.

A097061.name: Carmichael numbers C such that C-1 is not a Niven/Harshad number.
formula: a(n) = if(sum of digits(n-1))/number of digits<>int(sum of digits(n-1)/number of digits, n, 0)

A097062.name: Interleave 2*n+1 and 2*n-1.
formula: a(n) = 2*(n-1) - a(n-1), with a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Nov 16 2010

A097063.name: Expansion of (1-2*x+3*x^2)/((1+x)*(1-x)^3).
formula: a(n) = binomial(n+1, 2) - ceiling((n+1)/2) + 2((n+1) mod 2). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Mar 08 2014
a(n) = 2*floor(n/2) + ceiling((n-1)^2/2). - _M. Ryan Julian Jr._, Sep 10 2019
a(n) = A326296(n + 1, n) for n > 0. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Sep 23 2019

A097065.name: Interleave n+1 and n-1.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) - a(n-3) for n > 2. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jan 10 2017

A097068.name: a(n)=Sum(C(n,2k+1)5^k 3^(2k+1) 7^(n-2k-1), k=0,..,Floor[(n-1)/2]).
formula: a(n)=2^(n-1)F(4n), where F(n) are Fibonacci numbers A000045

A097069.name: Positive integers n such that 2n - 9 is prime.
formula: Half of p+9 where p is a prime greater than 2.

A097070.name: Consider all compositions (ordered partitions) of n into n parts, allowing zeros. E.g., for n = 3 we get 300, 030, 003, 210, 120, 201, 102, 021, 012, 111. Then a(n) is the total number of 1's.
formula: More generally, total number of k's (k>=0) in all ordered partitions of n into n parts, allowing zeros, is n*binomial(2*n-k-2, n-2) if n >= k, 0 otherwise.
Total number of 0's is given by A005430.
a(n) = n*A088218(n-1) for n > 0. - _Werner Schulte_, Jan 22 2017

A097073.name: Expansion of (1-x+2*x^2)/((1+x)*(1-2*x)).
formula: G.f.: 1 - x + x*Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 + 2*x^2 + (4*k+5)*x - x*(4*k+1 + 2*x)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 07 2013

A097074.name: Expansion of (1-x+2x^2)/((1-x)(1-x-2x^2)).
formula: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + a(n-2) - 2*a(n-3), a(0)=1=a(1), a(2)=5. Observed by G. Detlefs. See the W. Lang link. (End)

A097076.name: Expansion of x/(1-x-3x^2-x^3).
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 3*a(n-2) + a(n-3). [corrected by Paul Curtz, Mar 04 2008]

A097077.name: a(n) has the property that when multiplied by an appropriate n-digit number the product is the n-digit number repeated 6 times.

A097078.name: Decimal expansion of positive real number x such that Dedekind eta(sqrt(-1)*x) is maximized.

A097079.name: Decimal expansion of the maximum value of Dedekind eta(sqrt(-1)*x), x > 0.

A097080.name: a(n) = 2*n^2 - 2*n + 3.
formula: a(n) = 4*(n-1) + a(n-1) for n>1, a(1)=3. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Nov 16 2010

A097082.name: Number of permutations p of (1,2,3,...,n) such that k+p(k) is a Fibonacci number for 1<=k<=n.
formula: a(n) = permanent(m), where the n X n matrix m is defined by m(i,j) = 1 or 0 depending on whether i+j is a Fibonacci number or not.

A097083.name: Values of k such that there is exactly one permutation p of (1,2,3,...,k) such that i+p(i) is a Fibonacci number for 1<=i<=k.
formula: It appears that {a(n)} satisfies a(1)=1, a(2)=2 and, for n>2, a(n) = F(n+2) - a(n-2) - 1, where {F(k)} is the sequence of Fibonacci numbers, i.e, that the sequence is the partial sums of A006498.
If the partial sum assumption is correct: a(n) = floor(phi^(n+3)/5), where phi=(1+sqrt(5))/2 = A001622, and a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) + ( (n*(n+1)/2) mod 2). - _Gary Detlefs_, Mar 12 2011
If the partial sum assumption is correct: a(n)= +2*a(n-1) -a(n-2) +a(n-3) -a(n-5).
Conjecture: a(n) = floor(F(n+3)/sqrt(5)), where F(n) = A000045(n) are Fibonacci numbers. - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Nov 05 2015

A097084.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the n-th diagonal equals the n-th row transformed by triangle A008459 (squared binomial coefficients).

A097085.name: Row sums of triangle A097084, in which the n-th diagonal equals the n-th row transformed by triangle A008459 (squared binomial coefficients).
formula: a(n) = Sum_{j=0..n} A263897(j). - _Gregory L. Simay_, Oct 30 2015

A097086.name: Unreduced numerators of coefficients a(n)/2^A097087(n)*1/n! in function F(x) that satisfies F(F(x)) = x*exp(x).
formula: E.g.f.: F(x) = Sum_{n>=0} a(n)/2^A097087(n)*x^n/n! where F(F(x)) = x*exp(x).

A097087.name: Exponents of 2 in the unreduced denominators of coefficients A097086(n)/2^a(n)*1/n! in function F(x) that satisfies F(F(x)) = x*exp(x).
formula: E.g.f.: F(x) = Sum_{n>=0} A097086(n)/2^a(n)*x^n/n! where F(F(x)) = x*exp(x).

A097088.name: Numerators of coefficients in function A(x) such that A(A(x)) = x+x^2.
formula: a(n) = numerator(T(n,1)) if n>0, a(0) = 1, where T(n,m) = 1 if n=m, else T(n,m) = C(m,n-m) - Sum_{i=m+1..n-1} T(n,i)*T(i,m)/2. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Nov 08 2011

A097089.name: Exponents of 2 that form the denominators of coefficients in function A(x) such that A(A(x)) = x+x^2.

A097090.name: G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(A(x)) = x*(1+2*x)^2.
formula: a(n)=T(n,1), T(n,m)=if n=m then 1 else 1/2*(binomial(2*m,n-m)*2^(n-m)-sum(i=m+1..n-1, T(n,i)*T(i,m))). [From Vladimir Kruchinin, Nov 10 2011]

A097091.name: Number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly three times.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{m>0} (x^(3*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). More generally, g.f. for number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly k times is Sum_{m>0} (x^(k*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). _Vladeta Jovovic_

A097092.name: Number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly four times.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{m>0} (x^(4*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). More generally, g.f. for number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly k times is Sum_{m>0} (x^(k*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). _Vladeta Jovovic_

A097093.name: Number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly five times.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{m>0} (x^(5*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). More generally, g.f. for number of partitions of n such that the least part occurs exactly k times is Sum_{m>0} (x^(k*m) / Product_{i>m} (1-x^i)). _Vladeta Jovovic_

A097094.name: Triangle, read by rows, where the self-convolution of the antidiagonal sums (A097097) equals the row sums (A097096); the row sums also equals the convolution of the main diagonal (A097095) with the Fibonacci sequence (A000045).
formula: T(n, 0) = 1 and T(n, n) = A097095(n) for n>=0; T(n, k) = T(n-1, k) + T(n-2, k-1) for n>k>=1. G.f.: A(x, y) = A097095(x*y)/(1-x-x^2*y), where A097095(x)/(1-x-x^2) = A097095(x^2)^2/(1-x-x^3)^2 and A097095(x) is the g.f. of the main diagonal.

A097095.name: Main diagonal of triangle A097094; g.f. A(x) satisfies A(x)/(1-x-x^2) = A(x^2)^2/(1-x-x^3)^2.
formula: G.f.: A(x)/(1-x-x^2) = g.f. of A097096 (row sums of A097094); G.f.: A(x^2)/(1-x-x^3) = g.f. of A097097 (antidiagonal sums of A097094).

A097096.name: Row sums of triangle A097094 and also equals the self-convolution of A097097 (antidiagonal sums of triangle A097094).
formula: G.f.: A(x) = A097095(x)/(1-x-x^2) = A097095(x^2)^2/(1-x-x^3)^2, where A097095(x) is the g.f. of the main diagonal of triangle A097094.

A097097.name: Antidiagonal sums of triangle A097094, where self-convolution forms A097096 (row sums of triangle A097094).
formula: G.f.: A(x) = A097095(x^2)/(1-x-x^3), where A097095(x) is the g.f. of the main diagonal of triangle A097094.

A097098.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of peakless Motzkin paths of length n and having a total of k level steps (1,0) to the left of the first (1,1) step and to the right of the last (1,-1) step (i.e., total length of the two tails is k; can be easily expressed in terms of RNA secondary structure terminology).
formula: T(n,k) = (k+1)T(n-k, 0) for k < n; T(n,n) = 1. T(n,0) = a(n)-2a(n-1) + a(n-2) (n >= 2), where a(n) = Sum_{k=ceiling((n+1)/2)..n} binomial(k, n-k)*binomial(k, n-k+1)/k = A004148(n).
G.f.: 1/(1-tz) + (1-z)(g-1-zg)/(1-tz)^2, where g = (1 - z + z^2 - sqrt(1 - 2z - z^2 - 2z^3 + z^4))/(2z^2) is the g.f. of the RNA secondary structure numbers (A004148).

A097099.name: Smallest k>0 such that (2^k)*A002110(n) - 1 is prime.

A097100.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of peakless Motzkin paths of length n containing k subwords of the type U H^j U or D H^j D for some j>0, where U=(1,1), H=(1,0) and D=(1,-1) (can be easily expressed using RNA secondary structure terminology).

A097101.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 7 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 7 ways.

A097102.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 13 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 13 ways.

A097103.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 22 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 22 ways.

A097104.name: Start with positive integers in order. At m-th iteration, let a(k) become a(k-1) for m+1<=k<=p_m and let a(m) become a(p_m), where p_m is the m-th prime. Record the limiting sequence.

A097105.name: Gregorian years containing "blue" Islamic New Year Days. The boundary of a calendrical period is hereby called "blue" w.r.t. a similarly named period in another calendar when the shorter one does not contain the boundaries of the longer one. Gregorian calendar prior to 1582 is proleptic, extrapolated according to the calculator in the links.

A097106.name: a(n) = (Smallest prime power >= n) - (greatest prime power <= n).
formula: a(n) = 0 iff n is a power of a prime (in A000961).

A097107.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = number of peakless Motzkin paths of length n and containing a total of k level steps H in all DHH...HU's, where U=(1,1), H=(1,0) and D=(1,-1) (can be easily expressed using RNA secondary structure terminology).

A097108.name: If a geodesic dome is made by dividing each triangle of an icosahedron into n^2 identical equilateral triangles and the vertices of those newly created triangles are pushed out from the center to lie on the surface of the sphere in which the icosahedron is inscribed, then this sequence gives the number of different strut lengths that are required to build the dome.
formula: Satisfies a linear recurrence with characteristic polynomial (1+x^3)(1-x^3)^3.
A045943(n) = a(3*(n-1)), n<>1. - _Gonzalo Rodríguez Whipple_, May 30 2010

A097109.name: G.f.: s(2)^2*s(3)^3/(s(1)*s(6)^2), where s(k) := subs(q=q^k, eta(q)) and eta(q) is Dedekind's function, cf. A010815.
formula: Fine gives an explicit formula for a(n) in terms of the divisors of n.
Expansion of (a(q) - 3*a(q^3) - 4*a(q^4) + 12*a(q^12)) / 6 in powers of q where a() is a cubic AGM theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 15 2006
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [ 1, -1, -2, -1, 1, -2, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 15 2006
a(n) is multiplicative with a(2^e) = -3(1+(-1)^e)/2 if e>0, a(3^e) = -2 if e>0, a(p^e) = e+1 if p == 1 (mod 6), a(p^e) = (1+(-1)^e)/2 if p == 5 (mod 6). - _Michael Somos_, Sep 15 2006

A097125.name: Number of noncongruent integer-sided tetrahedra with largest side n.

A097126.name: Number of noncongruent integer-sided 4-dimensional simplices with largest side n.

A097127.name: Number of noncongruent integer-sided 5-dimensional simplices with largest side n.

A097128.name: Number of noncongruent n-dimensional integer-sided simplices with diameter 3.

A097129.name: Number of noncongruent n-dimensional integer-sided simplices with diameter 4.

A097130.name: Carmichael numbers that are not == 1 mod 24.

A097134.name: a(n) = 3*Fibonacci(2*n) + 0^n.
formula: a(n) = Fibonacci(6*n) - 5*Fibonacci(2*n)^3 for n > 0. - _Gary Detlefs_, Oct 18 2011

A097135.name: a(0) = 1; for n>0, a(n) = 3*Fibonacci(n).
formula: a(n) = L(n+1)-F(n-1) for n>=1, where L=A000032 and F=A000045. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Sep 17 2015

A097140.name: Interleave n and 1-n.
formula: G.f.: x*G(0)/(1+x) where G(k) = 1 + 2*x/(1 - x/(x + 2/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 21 2012

A097141.name: Expansion of x*(1+2*x)/(1+x)^2.
formula: a(n) = A099570(n) for n > 1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 15 2008
a(n) = A038608(n-2) for n > 2. - _Georg Fischer_, Oct 06 2018

A097142.name: Number of primes p < 10^n for which 2 is a cubic residue (mod p).

A097143.name: a(n) is the least prime greater than a(n-1) such that n is a quadratic residue mod p.

A097145.name: Total sum of minimum list sizes in all sets of lists of n-set, cf. A000262.

A097146.name: Total sum of maximum list sizes in all sets of lists of n-set, cf. A000262.

A097147.name: Total sum of minimum block sizes in all partitions of n-set.

A097148.name: Total sum of maximum block sizes in all partitions of n-set.

A097149.name: Numbers n such that Galois group of polynomial x^8+n*x^4+1 is E(8) (the group C_2 X C_2 X C_2).

A097150.name: Digits of balanced base-10 representations of nonnegative integers (most significant digits first).

A097151.name: Digits of balanced base-10 representations of nonnegative integers (least significant digits first).

A097152.name: Smallest prime p greater than n for which n is a quadratic residue mod p.

A097153.name: Reversal of n minus largest digit of n.

A097154.name: Number of iterations of f(x) = reverse(x) - maxdigit(x) needed to reach zero, or -1 if zero is never reached, where maxdig(n) is the largest digit of n.

A097155.name: Numbers that reach the fixed point 89 under iteration of f(x) = reverse(x) - maxdigit(x).

A097156.name: Least number that requires exactly n iterations of f(x) = reverse(x) - maxdigit(x) to reach zero.

A097157.name: Number of iterations of f(x) = reverse(x) - maxdigit(x) needed for the numbers in A097155 to reach 89.

A097158.name: Numbers that set a new record for iterations needed to reach 0 under f(x) = reverse(x) - maxdigit(x).

A097159.name: Smallest prime p such that there are n consecutive quadratic residues mod p.

A097160.name: Greatest prime p such that there are n, but not n+1, consecutive quadratic residues mod p, or -1 if no such prime exists.

A097161.name: Number of primes modulo which the largest number of consecutive quadratic residues is n.

A097170.name: Total number of minimal vertex covers among labeled trees on n nodes.
formula: Coulomb and Bauer give a g.f.

A097171.name: Number of maximal matchings among labeled trees on n nodes.
formula: Coulomb and Bauer give a g.f.

A097172.name: Total number of brown nodes among tricolored labeled trees on n nodes.

A097173.name: Total number of green nodes among tricolored labeled trees on n nodes.
formula: E.g.f.: A(x) = T(-T(x))^2, with T(x)=Sum[k=1..inf, A000169(k)/k!*x^k].

A097174.name: Total number of red nodes among tricolored labeled trees on n nodes.

A097179.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives coefficients of polynomial R_n(y) that satisfies R_n(1/2) = 4^n, where R_n(y) forms the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A077860(y)^(n+1).

A097180.name: Row sums of triangle A097179, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A077860(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/2) = 4^n for all n>=0.

A097181.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives coefficients of polynomial R_n(y) that satisfies R_n(1/2) = 8^n, where R_n(y) forms the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097182(y)^(n+1).

A097182.name: G.f. A(x) has the property that the first (n+1) terms of A(x)^(n+1) form the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) of triangle A097181 and satisfy R_n(1/2) = 8^n for all n>=0.

A097183.name: Main diagonal of triangle A097181, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097182(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/2) = 8^n for all n>=0.

A097184.name: G.f. A(x) satisfies A097182(x*A(x)) = A(x) and so equals the ratio of the g.f.s of any two adjacent diagonals of triangle A097181.
formula: D-finite with recurrence: (n+1)*a(n) +2*(-8*n+1)*a(n-1)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 16 2012

A097185.name: Row sums of triangle A097181, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097182(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/2) = 8^n for all n>=0.

A097186.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives coefficients of polynomial R_n(y) that satisfies R_n(1/3) = 3^n, where R_n(y) forms the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A057083(y)^(n+1).

A097187.name: Antidiagonal sums of triangle A097186, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A057083(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/3) = 3^n for all n>=0.

A097188.name: G.f. A(x) satisfies A057083(x*A(x)) = A(x) and so equals the ratio of the g.f.s of any two adjacent diagonals of triangle A097186.
formula: x*A(x) is the compositional inverse of x-3*x^2+3*x^3. - _Ira M. Gessel_, Feb 18 2012
a(n) = 1/(n+1) * Sum_{k=1..n} binomial(k,n-k) * 3^(k)*(-1)^(n-k) * binomial(n+k,n), if n>0; a(0)=1. - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, Feb 07 2011
a(n) = 9^n * Gamma(n+2/3) / ((n+1) * Gamma(2/3) * Gamma(n+1)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Feb 09 2014

A097189.name: Row sums of triangle A097186, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A057083(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/3) = 3^n for all n >= 0.

A097190.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives coefficients of polynomial R_n(y) that satisfies R_n(1/3) = 9^n, where R_n(y) forms the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097191(y)^(n+1).

A097191.name: G.f. A(x) has the property that the first (n+1) terms of A(x)^(n+1) form the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) of triangle A097190 and satisfy R_n(1/3) = 9^n for all n>=0.
formula: G.f. satisfies: A(x) = G(x/A(x)) where G(x) = A(x*G(x)) is the g.f. of A097193.

A097192.name: Main diagonal of triangle A097190, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097191(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/3) = 9^n for all n>=0.

A097193.name: G.f. A(x) satisfies A097191(x*A(x)) = A(x) and so equals the ratio of the g.f.s of any two adjacent diagonals of triangle A097190.

A097194.name: Row sums of triangle A097190, in which the n-th row polynomial R_n(y) is formed from the initial (n+1) terms of g.f. A097191(y)^(n+1), where R_n(1/3) = 9^n for all n>=0.

A097195.name: Expansion of s(12)^3*s(18)^2/(s(6)^2*s(36)), where s(k) := subs(q=q^k, eta(q)) and eta(q) is Dedekind's function, cf. A010815. Then replace q^6 with q.
formula: Expansion of q^(-1/6) * eta(q^2)^3 * eta(q^3)^2 / (eta(q)^2 * eta(q^6)) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 05 2016
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [ 2, -1, 0, -1, 2, -2, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Mar 05 2016
Fine gives an explicit formula for a(n) in terms of the divisors of n.
a(n) = b(6*n + 1) where b() is multiplicative with b(2^e) = b(3^e) = 0^e, b(p^e) = e+1 if p == 1 (mod 6), b(p^e) = (1 + (-1)^e)/2 if p == 5 (mod 6).
G.f.: Sum_{k} x^k / (1 - x^(6*k + 1)). - _Michael Somos_, Nov 03 2005

A097196.name: Expansion of psi(x^3)^2 / f(-x^2) in powers of x where psi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
formula: Expansion of q^(-2/3) * eta(x^6)^4 / (eta(x^2) * eta(x^3)^2) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Jul 14 2015

A097197.name: Expansion of q^(-1/3) * eta(q^6)^2 / (eta(q) * eta(q^3)) in powers of q.
formula: Expansion of psi(q^3) / f(-q) in powers of q where psi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Euler transform of period 6 sequence [ 1, 1, 2, 1, 1, 0, ...]. - _Michael Somos_, Aug 19 2006
G.f.: Product_{k>0} (1 + x^k + x^(2*k)) * (1 + x^(3*k))^2. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 10 2008

A097199.name: Numbers of the form p^4 + 4^p for p prime.

A097200.name: Numbers of the form p^5 + 5^p for p prime.

A097201.name: Numbers of the form 4^p - p^4 for p prime.

A097202.name: Numbers of the form 5^p - p^5 for p prime.

A097203.name: Number of 4-tuples (a,b,c,d) with 1 <= a <= b <= c <= d, a^2+b^2+c^2+d^2 = n and gcd(a,b,c,d) = 1.
formula: If a(n) > 0 then 8 does not divide n.

a(n) = k if there are k different quadruples [s(1),s(2),s(3),s(4)] with 1 <= s(1) <= s(2) <= s(3) <= s(4), gcd(s(1),s(2),s(3),s(4)) = 1 and sum(s(j)^2,j=1..4) = n. If there is no such quadruple then a(n) = 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Mar 25 2013

A097204.name: Binomial transform of A033312.
formula: a(n) = exp(1)*Gamma(n+1, 1) - 2^n and a(n) ~ exp(1)*n! - 2^n. - _Peter Luschny_, Sep 02 2014

A097205.name: Numbers of the form 3^p * p^3 for p prime.

A097206.name: Numbers of the form 5^p * p^5 for p prime.

A097207.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) = binomial(n,k) + 2*binomial(n,k-1).
formula: T(n,k) = A029635(n+1,k), 0 <= k <= n. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Mar 12 2012

A097208.name: a(n) is the least k such that A098598(k) = n.

A097209.name: Primes of the form (10^p + 1)/11 (corresponding p are in A001562).

A097211.name: a(n) = the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of A025487(n), i.e., A076078(A025487(n)).

A097212.name: Numbers n such that A076078(n) > A076078(m) for all m < n, A076078(n) being the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of n.

A097213.name: Members of A097212, excluding highly composite numbers (A002182).

A097214.name: Numbers m such that A076078(m) = m, where A076078(m) equals the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of m.

A097215.name: Numbers m such that A076078(m) = m and bigomega(m) >= 2; or in other words, A097214, excluding powers of 2.

A097216.name: Numbers n such that A076078(n) > n, where A076078(n) equals the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of n.

A097217.name: Odd numbers n such that A076078(n) > n, where A076078(n) equals the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of n.

A097218.name: Numbers n such that A076078(n) < n, where A076078(n) equals the number of sets of distinct positive integers with a least common multiple of n.

A097219.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 6 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 6 ways.

A097220.name: Numbers n such that pi(n) = product of digits of n.

A097221.name: Numbers n such that for some k and a_1,a_2,...,a_k the concatenation of the a_i is equal to n and their product is equal to pi(n).

A097222.name: Numbers n such that for some k there exist k numbers a1,a2, ...,ak that concatenations of them is equal to n and sum of them is equal to Pi(n).

A097223.name: Prime numbers p such that p = prime(n) and n = product of the digits of p.

A097225.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 10 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 10 ways.

A097226.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 12 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 12 ways.

A097227.name: Numbers n such that n = prime(d_1) * prime(d_2) * ... * prime(d_k), where d_1 d_2 ... d_k is the decimal expansion of n.

A097228.name: Numbers n such that the product of digits of n equals the concatenation of pi(d)'s where d runs through the digits of n.

A097229.name: Triangle read by rows: number of Motzkin paths by length and by number of humps.

A097230.name: Triangle read by rows: number of binary sequences with no isolated 1's.

A097231.name: Number of solutions (excluding rotations and reflections) for a series of 9 consecutive primes beginning with the n-th prime arranged in a 3 X 3 square such that all row, column and diagonal totals are primes.

A097232.name: Starting primes for which there are no solutions in A097231.
formula: a(n) = the n-th starting prime for which there are no solutions in A097231.

A097233.name: Starting primes for which there is only one solution in A097231.

A097234.name: Numerators of coefficients in cosh(x) / sin(x) power series.

A097235.name: Denominators of coefficients in cosh(x) / sin(x) power series.

A097236.name: Number of hierarchical orderings ("societies") with at least 2 elements ("individuals") on each level for n labeled elements.

A097237.name: Number of hierarchical orderings ("societies") of n labeled elements ("individuals") with at least two occupied levels.

A097238.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 16 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 16 ways.

A097239.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 17 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 17 ways.

A097242.name: Expansion of q-series 1 / (q^2, q^3, q^9, q^10; q^12)_infinity.
formula: Expansion of chi(x^3) / chi(-x^2) in powers of x where chi() is a Ramanujan theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 17 2006
Expansion of q^(1/24) * eta(q^4) * eta(q^6)^2 / (eta(q^2) * eta(q^3) * eta(q^12)) in powers of q.

A097243.name: Expansion of 1 + 32 * (eta(q^4) / eta(q))^8 in powers of q.
formula: G.f. A(x) satisfies 0 = f(A(x), A(x^2)) where f(u, v) = (u+3)^2 - 8*(u+1)*v^2.
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (4 t)) = 1/8 g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A007248. - _Michael Somos_, Dec 15 2016

A097244.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 31 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 31 ways.

A097245.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 37 distinct integer-sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 37 ways.

A097246.name: Replace factors of n that are squares of a prime with the prime succeeding this prime.
formula: Multiplicative with p^e -> NextPrime(p)^floor(e/2) * p^(e mod 2), where p prime and NextPrime(p)=A000040(A049084(p)+1).

A097248.name: a(n) is the eventual stable point reached when iterating k -> A097246(k), starting from k = n.
formula: If A008683(n) <> 0 [when n is squarefree], a(n) = n, otherwise a(n) = a(A097246(n)).
If A277885(n) = 0, a(n) = n, otherwise a(n) = a(A277886(n)).
a(1) = 1; a(p) = p, for prime p; a(m*k) = A331590(a(m), a(k)).

A097249.name: a(n) is the number of times we must iterate A097246, starting at n, before the result is squarefree.
formula: If A008966(n) = 1 [when n is in A005117], a(n) = 0, otherwise a(n) = 1 + a(A097246(n)). - _Antti Karttunen_, Jul 29 2018

A097250.name: Smallest m such that A097249(m) = n; from n=1 onwards, twice the primorials, 2*A002110(n).

A097251.name: Numbers whose set of base 5 digits is {0,4}.

A097252.name: Numbers whose set of base 6 digits is {0,5}.

A097253.name: Numbers whose set of base 7 digits is {0,6}.

A097254.name: Numbers whose set of base 8 digits is {0,7}.

A097255.name: Numbers whose set of base 9 digits is {0,8}.

A097256.name: Numbers whose set of base 10 digits is {0,9}.

A097257.name: Numbers whose set of base 11 digits is {0,A}, where A base 11 = 10 base 10.

A097258.name: Numbers whose set of base 12 digits is {0,B}, where B base 12 = 11 base 10.

A097259.name: Numbers whose set of base 13 digits is {0,C}, where C base 13 = 12 base 10.

A097260.name: Numbers whose set of base 14 digits is {0,D}, where D base 14 = 13 base 10.

A097261.name: Numbers whose set of base 15 digits is {0,E}, where E base 15 = 14 base 10.

A097262.name: Numbers whose set of base 16 digits is {0,F}, where F base 16 = 15 base 10.

A097263.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives odd leg values.

A097264.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives short even leg values.

A097265.name: Primitive Pythagorean Quadruples a^2+b^2+c^2=d^2, 0<a<=b<=c<=d, gcd(a,b,c,d)=1, sorted by d, then c, then b; sequence gives long even leg values.

A097266.name: Number of primitive Pythagorean quadruples with diagonal 2n+1.

A097267.name: Least positive integer that is the diagonal of n primitive Pythagorean quadruples, or zero if no such integer exists.

A097268.name: Numbers that are both the sum of two nonzero squares and the difference of two nonzero squares.

A097269.name: Numbers that are the sum of two nonzero squares but not the difference of two nonzero squares.

A097270.name: Numbers that are the difference of two nonzero squares but not the sum of two nonzero squares.

A097271.name: Numbers that are neither the sum of two nonzero squares nor the difference of two nonzero squares.

A097272.name: Least integer with same "mod 2 prime signature" as n.

A097273.name: Least integer with each "mod 2 prime signature".

A097274.name: Least integer "mod 2 prime signatures" k ordered by number of Pythagorean triples with leg = k.

A097275.name: Least integer "mod 2 prime signatures" k ordered by number of primitive Pythagorean triples with leg = k.

A097276.name: Least k such that the least common multiple of the numbers 1+n,1+2n,...1+kn is different from the denominator of 1 + 1/(1+n) + 1/(1+2n) +...+1/(1+kn).

A097277.name: a(n) = number of permutations <p(1), p(2), ..., p(n)> of <1, 2, ..., n>, such that p(k) > p(k-1) when k is composite and p(k) < p(k-1) when k is prime.
formula: a(n) = n-th row sum of A097278.

A097278.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n, k) = number of permutations <p(1), p(2), ..., p(n)> of <1, 2, ..., n> that end with k, such that p(k) > p(k-1) when k is composite and p(k) < p(k-1) when k is prime. (n > 0, 1 <= k <= n).
formula: T(1, 1) = 1, T(n, k) = sum(i = k..(n-1), T(n-1, i)) if n is prime, T(n, k) = sum(i = 1..(k-1), T(n-1, i)) if n is composite.

A097280.name: Perimeter of integer triangle (A001611(n), A001611(n+1), A001611(n+2)).

A097281.name: Integer part of the area of integer triangle [A001611(n), A001611(n+1), A001611(n+2)].
formula: a(n) = floor(sqrt(s(n) * (s(n)-A001611(n)) * (s(n)-A001611(n+1)) * (s(n)-A001611(n+2)))), where s(n) is the semiperimeter: s(n) = A097280(n)/2.

A097282.name: Numbers n that are the hypotenuse of exactly 40 distinct integer sided right triangles, i.e., n^2 can be written as a sum of two squares in 40 ways.

A097283.name: Contains exactly once every pair (i,j) satisfying 0 < i < j.

A097284.name: Rectangular array T by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of k-th n in A097283.

A097285.name: Contains exactly once every pair (i,j) of distinct positive integers.
formula: Juxtapose segments: 1 2, then 1 3 2 3, then 1 4 2 4 3 4. General segment is 1 n 2 n ... n-1 n, followed by 1, so that clearly, every i<j and every i>j is uniquely present.

A097286.name: Rectangular array T by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of k-th n in A097285.

A097287.name: Rectangular array T by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of n where (n,k) occurs in A097285, for distinct n,k and T(n,n)=0 for all n.

A097288.name: Rectangular array read by antidiagonals obtained from A097287 by deleting the zeros.

A097289.name: Contains exactly once every pair (i,j) satisfying 0 < i <= j.
formula: Obtained from A097283 by inserting m right after the first occurrence of m, for each positive integer m.

A097290.name: Rectangular array T, by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of k-th n in A097289.

A097291.name: Contains exactly once every pair (i,j) of positive integers.

A097292.name: Rectangular array T, by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of n in A097291 at which the pair (n,k) occurs.

A097293.name: Contains exactly once every triple i,j,k such that 0<i<j<k.
formula: Terms are lexically ordered in triples by sum: 1 2 3 (sum = 6) 1 2 4 (sum = 7) 1 2 5, then 1 3 4 (two triples having sum = 8), etc.

A097294.name: Contains exactly once every triple i,j,k such that i>j>k>0.
formula: Obtained by reversing triples in A097293.

A097295.name: Length of longest non-overlapping repeated subword of n in binary representation.

A097296.name: Numbers n such that A001055(n) divides n.
formula: Luca et al. estimate the density of this sequence (see their Theorem 3).

A097301.name: Numerators of rationals used in the Euler-Maclaurin type derivation of Stirling's formula for N!.
formula: a(n)=numerator(B(n)) with B(n):=Bernoulli(2*n+2)*(2*n)!/(2*n+2) and Bernoulli(n)= A027641(n)/A027642(n).

A097302.name: Denominators of rationals used in the Euler-Maclaurin type derivation of Stirling's formula for N!.
formula: a(n)=denominator(B(n)) with B(n):=Bernoulli(2*n+2)*(2*n)!/(2*n+2) and Bernoulli(n)= A027641(n)/A027642(n).

A097303.name: Denominators in Stirling's asymptotic series.
formula: a(n) = denominator(s(n)), where the signed rationals s(n) are the coefficients of ((1/z)^k)/k! in the asymptotic series appearing in Stirling's formula for GAMMA(z).

A097304.name: Triangle of numbers of partitions of n with m parts which are all odd.
formula: T(n, m) := 0 if 1 <= n < m, else T(n, m) = number of partitions of n with m parts which are all odd. Hence T(2*k, 2*j-1) = 0, k >= 1, k >= j >= 1; T(2*k-1, 2*j) = 0, k >= 1, k-1 >= j >= 1.
T(n, k) = T(n-1, k-1) + T(n-2*k, k). If n+k is even, T(n, k) = A008284((n+k)/2, k) = A072233((n-k)/2, k); 0 otherwise. - _Álvar Ibeas_, Jul 25 2020

A097305.name: Array of number of partitions of n with odd parts only and largest part 2*m-1 with m in {1,2,..., ceiling(n/2)}.
formula: T(n, m)= number of partitions of n with only odd parts and largest part is k:=2*m-1, m=1, 2, ..., ceiling(n/2).

A097306.name: Array of number of partitions of n with odd parts not exceeding 2*m-1 with m in {1, 2, ..., ceiling(n/2)}.
formula: T(n, m) = number of partitions of n with odd parts only and largest parts <= 2*m-1 for m from {1, 2, ..., ceiling(n/2)}.

A097308.name: Chebyshev T-polynomials T(n,13) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n) = T(n, 13) = (S(n, 26) - S(n-2, 26))/2 = S(n, 26) - 13*S(n-1, 26) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp. second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 26)=A097309(n).
a(n) = (ap^n + am^n)/2 with ap := 13+2*sqrt(42) and am := 13-2*sqrt(42).

A097309.name: Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind, U(n,x), evaluated at x=13.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 26) = U(n, 13), n >= -1, with Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind. See A049310 for the triangle of S(n, x) coefficients. S(-1, x) := 0 =: U(-1, x).
a(n) = 26*a(n-1) - a(n-2), a(-1)=0, a(0)=1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 18 2008
With an offset of 0, product {n >= 1} (1 + 1/a(n)) = 1/6*(6 + sqrt(42)). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 23 2012

A097310.name: Chebyshev T-polynomials T(n,14) with Diophantine property.
formula: a(n)= T(n, 14)= (S(n, 28)-S(n-2, 28))/2 = S(n, 28)-14*S(n-1, 28) with T(n, x), resp. S(n, x), Chebyshev's polynomials of the first, resp.second, kind. See A053120 and A049310. S(n, 28)=A097311(n).
a(n)= (ap^n + am^n)/2 with ap := 14+sqrt(195) and am := 14-sqrt(195).

A097311.name: Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind, U(n,x), evaluated at x=14.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 28) = U(n, 14), n>=-1, with Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind. See A049310 for the triangle of S(n, x) coefficients. S(-1, x) := 0 =: U(-1, x).
With an offset of 0, product {n >= 1} (1 + 1/a(n)) = 1/13*(13 + sqrt(195)). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 23 2012

A097312.name: Numbers with property that can bring the first digit to the back of the number to get a prime (zeros are dropped).

A097313.name: Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind, U(n,x), evaluated at x=15.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 30) = U(n, 15), n>=-1, with Chebyshev polynomials of 2nd kind. See A049310 for the triangle of S(n, x) coefficients. S(-1, x) := 0 =: U(-1, x).
a(n) = 30*a(n-1)-a(n-2) for n>0; a(-1)=0, a(0)=1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 18 2008
With an offset of 0, product {n >= 1} (1 + 1/a(n)) = 1/7*(7 + 2*sqrt(14)). - _Peter Bala_, Dec 23 2012

A097314.name: Pell equation solutions (3*a(n))^2 - 10*b(n)^2 = -1 with b(n) = A097315(n), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 38) + S(n-1, 38) = S(2*n, 2*sqrt(10)), with Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind. See A049310 for the triangle of S(n, x) = U(n, x/2) coefficients. S(-1, x) := 0 =: U(-1, x).
a(n) = (-1)^n*T(2*n + 1, 3*i)/(3*i) with the imaginary unit i and Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind. See the T-triangle A053120.

A097315.name: Pell equation solutions (3*b(n))^2 - 10*a(n)^2 = -1 with b(n) = A097314(n), n >= 0.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 38) - S(n-1, 38) = T(2*n+1, sqrt(10))/sqrt(10), with Chebyshev polynomials of the second and first kind. See A049310 for the triangle of S(n, x)= U(n, x/2) coefficients. S(-1, x) := 0 =: U(-1, x); and A053120 for the T-triangle.
a(n) = ((-1)^n)*S(2*n, 6*i) with the imaginary unit i and Chebyshev polynomials S(n, x) with coefficients shown in A049310.
a(n) = 38*a(n-1) - a(n-2) for n > 1. - _Philippe Deléham_, Nov 18 2008

A097316.name: Chebyshev U(n,x) polynomial evaluated at x=33.
formula: a(n) = S(n, 66) with S(n, x) := U(n, x/2), Chebyshev's polynomials of the second kind. See A049310.

A097317.name: Numbers of the form 7^p + p^7 for p prime.

A097318.name: Numbers with more than one prime factor and, in the ordered factorization, the exponent never increases when read from left to right.

A097319.name: Numbers with more than one prime factor and, in the ordered factorization, the exponents are strictly increasing.

A097320.name: Numbers with more than one prime factor and, in the ordered factorization, the exponent always decreases when read from left to right.

A097322.name: (2n)! divided by denominator of Taylor expansion of exp(cos(x)-1).

A097323.name: One sixth of the unitary sociable numbers.

A097324.name: Numbers n such that A067655(n) is different from A049606(n).

A097325.name: Period 6: repeat [0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1].
formula: Recurrence: a(n+6) = a(n), a(0) = 0, a(i) = 1, 1 <= i <= 5.
For the general case: the characteristic function of numbers that are not multiples of m is a(n) = floor((n-1)/m) - floor(n/m) + 1, m, n > 0. - _Boris Putievskiy_, May 08 2013
a(n) = sign(n mod 6). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 29 2013
a(n) = ceiling(5n/6) - floor(5n/6). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 20 2014

A097326.name: Largest integer m such that m*n has the same decimal digit length as n.

A097327.name: Least positive integer m such that m*n has greater decimal digit length than n.

A097330.name: In the sequence of prime numbers replace each term p with floor(p/2) and ceiling(p/2).
formula: a(n) = 1 if n < 3, otherwise (prime((n + (n mod 2))/2) + 1)/2 - n mod 2.

A097331.name: Expansion of 1 + 2x/(1 + sqrt(1 - 4x^2)).
formula: Unsigned version of A090192, A105523. - _Philippe Deléham_, Sep 29 2006
G.f.: 1+xc(x^2), c(x) the g.f. of A000108;
G.f.: 1/(1-z/(1-z/(1-z/(...)))) where z=x/(1+2*x) (continued fraction); more generally g.f. C(x/(1+2*x)) where C(x) is the g.f. for the Catalan numbers (A000108). - _Joerg Arndt_, Mar 18 2011
Recurrence: (n+3)*a(n+2) = 4*n*a(n), a(0)=a(1)=1. For nonzero terms, a(n) ~ 2^(n+1)/((n+1)^(3/2)*sqrt(2*Pi)). - _Fung Lam_, Mar 17 2014

A097332.name: Expansion of (1/(1-x))(1+2x/(1-x+sqrt(1-2x-3x^2))).
formula: Conjecture D-finite with recurrence: (n+1)*a(n) - 3*n*a(n-1) + (-n+5)*a(n-2) + 3*(n-2)*a(n-3) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 26 2012

A097337.name: Integer part of the edge of a cube that has space-diagonal n.
formula: Let L be the length of the edges. Then sqrt(2)*L is the diagonal of a face. Whence n^2 = 2*L^2 + L^2, or n = sqrt(3)*L and L = n/sqrt(3).

A097338.name: Positive integers n such that 2n-11 is prime.
formula: Half of p+11 where p is a prime greater than 2.

A097340.name: McKay-Thompson series of class 4A for the Monster group with a(0) = 24.
formula: Expansion of q^(-1) * chi(q)^24 where chi() is a Ramanujan theta function.
Expansion of (eta(q^2)^2 / (eta(q) * eta(q^4)))^24 in powers of q.
G.f. is Fourier series of a level 4 modular function. f(-1 / (4 t)) = f(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t).
G.f. (1/q) * (Product_{k>0} (1 + q^(2k-1)))^24 = 64 * (G_n)^24 where q = e^(-Pi sqrt(n)) and G_n is a Ramanujan class invariant.

A097343.name: Triangle read by rows in which row n gives Legendre symbol (k,p) for 0<k<=p where p = n-th prime.

A097345.name: Numerators of the partial sums of the binomial transform of 1/(n+1).

A097346.name: Numerators of a Fibonacci related transform of 1/(n+1).

A097347.name: Rectangular array, by antidiagonals: T(n,k) = rank of k-th n in A097291.

A097349.name: Numbers n such that (Sum (2k)^k, k=1..n) + 1 is prime.

A097350.name: Numbers n such that (Sum (2k)^k, k=1..n) - 1 is prime.

A097351.name: Rectangular array T(n,k) by antidiagonals; rows are generalized Fibonacci sequences and every relatively prime pair (i,j) satisfying 1 <= i < j occurs exactly once.
formula: Recurrence for row n: T(n, k)=T(n, k-1)+T(n, k-2). Each row after the first begins with lexically least relatively prime pair not in previous rows.

A097352.name: Rectangular array T(n,k) by antidiagonals; rows are generalized Fibonacci sequences and every pair (i,j) satisfying 1 <= i < j occurs exactly once.
formula: Recurrence for row n: T(n, k)=T(n, k-1)+T(n, k-2). Each row after the first begins with lexically least pair not in previous rows.

A097353.name: Number of digits of the (10^n)-th tetranacci number (A000078(10^n)).
formula: a(n) = floor(log_10(r) + (10^n-2)*log_10(x)) + 1 for n >= 1, where x is the positive real root of the tetranacci limit equation x^4 - x^3 - x^2 - x - 1 = 0, x = 1.92756... and r is the positive real root of the tetranacci auxiliary equation 563r^4 - 20r^2 - 5r - 1 = 0, r = 0.293813... - Herman Jamke (hermanjamke(AT)fastmail.fm), May 01 2007

A097354.name: Slowest increasing sequence in which a(n) > a(n-1) is the smallest number requiring (n+1) characters in French.

A097355.name: Number of partitions of n into parts not greater than floor(log_2(n)).

A097356.name: Number of partitions of n into parts not greater than sqrt(n).

A097357.name: For definition see Comments lines.
formula: a(n+1) = Sum_{k=0..n} (T(n,k) mod 2) where T = A026300(Motzkin triangle), A064189, A084536, A091965, A110877, A125906, A126954. - _Philippe Deléham_, Apr 28 2007

A097358.name: Primes of the form 2(p+q) + 1, p and q prime.

A097359.name: a(n) is the number of partitions of n into parts not greater than A020639(n).

A097360.name: Number of partitions of n into parts not less than the smallest prime factor of n.

A097361.name: Primes of the form 2(p+q) - 1, where p and q are consecutive primes.

A097362.name: a(n) = (n+1)/2 if n is odd, n+2 otherwise.

A097363.name: Positive integers n such that 2n-13 is prime.
formula: Half of p+13 where p is a prime greater than 2.

A097364.name: Triangle read by rows, 0 <= k < n: T(n,k) = number of partitions of n such that the differences between greatest and smallest parts are k.
formula: G.f.: Sum_{i>=1} x^i/((1 - x^i)*Product_{j=1..i-1} (1 - t*x^j)). - _Emeric Deutsch_, Feb 23 2006

A097366.name: Largest k such that 2^k divides A096421(n).

A097367.name: Fibonacci regression array: For n>=2 and 1<=k<=n-1, T(n,k) is the last term before the first nonpositive term in the sequence n, k, n-k, 2k-n, 2n-3k, 5k-3n, ...
formula: For n > k >= 1, define d(1)=n, d(2)=k, d(j) = d(j-2) - d(j-1) for j >= 3. Then d(j) = F(j-2)*n - F(j-1)*k for odd j>=1 and d(j) = F(j-1)*k - F(j-2)*n for even j>=2, where F(h)=A000045(h) = h-th Fibonacci number. The sequence d is the aforementioned sequence n, k, n-k, 2k-n, 2n-3k, 5k-3n, ...

A097368.name: Least term in row n of the Fibonacci regression array in A097367.

A097369.name: Position in row n of Fibonacci regression array (A097367) where the least term first occurs.

A097370.name: Smallest number such that there exist exactly n triples (x,y,z) of distinct divisors with z=x+y.

A097371.name: Numbers n such that n=(d_1+5)(d_2+5)*...*(d_k+5), where d_1 d_2 ... d_k is the decimal expansion of n.

A097372.name: Numbers n such that n=(d_1+6)*(d_2+6)*...*(d_k+6) where d_1 d_2 ... d_k is the decimal expansion of n.

A097373.name: Numbers n such that there are no primes in a sequence formed from the t digits of n where the latter terms are given by rule b(i)=sum of t previous terms and the primes are counted from initial t digits up to the largest term < n^2; where zeros are located in A098598.

A097374.name: Perfect 4-composites: a perfect 4-composite is a natural number that can be represented in the form a^(a^(a^........(a^(a) ) ) ) for some natural number a and some number b>=1 of up-arrows.

A097376.name: Numbers n such that there is exactly one prime in a sequence formed from the t digits of n where the latter terms are given by rule b(i)=sum of t previous terms and the primes are counted from initial t digits up to the largest term < n^2; where ones are located in A098598.

A097379.name: Numbers m such that 1+SquareFreeKernel(m) is prime.

A097380.name: Numbers m such that 1+CubeFreeKernel(m) is prime.

A097381.name: Numbers m such that 1+SquareFreeKernel(m)*CubeFreeKernel(m) is prime.

A097382.name: a(h) = d(h,j) = lcm( f(h,j,1) ... f(h,j,h) ), when j=2.
formula: Given (1) f(h, j, a) = ( [ ((a/gcd(a, h)) / gcd(j+1, (a/gcd(a, h)))) * (h(j+1)) ] - [ ((a/gcd(a, h)) / gcd(j+1, (a/gcd(a, h)))) * (ja) ]) / a then let (2) a(h) = d(h, j) = lcm( f(h, j, 1) ... f(h, j, h) )

A097383.name: Minimum total number of comparisons to find each of the values 1 through n using a binary search with 3-way comparisons (less than, equal and greater than).
formula: Empirical: a(n+3)-a(n+2)-a(n+1)+a(n) = 1 if n = 2^k-3 or 2^k-2 for some k, 0 otherwise.

A097384.name: Total number of comparisons to find each of the values 1 through n using a binary search with 3-way comparisons (less than, equal and greater than), always choosing the mid-most value to compare to.

A097385.name: (Largest digit of n)^(smallest digit of n) + n.

A097386.name: Numbers n such that (largest digit of n)^(smallest digit of n) + n is prime.

A097387.name: Let f(x)=(largest digit of x)^(smallest digit of x) + x (A097385). Sequence gives numbers n such that f(n) and f(n+1) are both prime.

A097388.name: 2n-th derivative of the Gaussian exp(-x^2) evaluated at x=0.
formula: G.f.: 1/U(0) where U(k) = 1 + x*(2*k+2)/U(k+1); (continued fraction, 1-step). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Nov 14 2012
G.f.: 1/Q(0), where Q(k) = 1 - x*(8*k+2) + x*(8*k+4)/(1 - x*(8*k+6) + x*(8*k+8)/Q(k+1)); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 18 2013

A097390.name: Values of ordinal numbers in the following true sentence: "This sentence contains the twentieth, eighth, ninth, nineteenth ... letters of the English alphabet, in order.".

A097391.name: The number of hierarchies with at least one subhierarchy composed of exactly 2 levels and no subhierarchy with more than 2 levels.

A097392.name: The number of hierarchies with at least one subhierarchy composed of exactly 3 levels and no subhierarchy with more than 3 levels.

A097393.name: Emirpimes: numbers n such that n and its reversal are distinct semiprimes.

A097395.name: Values of ordinal numbers in the following true sentence: "The twentieth, eighth, fifth ... letters of the English alphabet appear in this sentence, in order.".

A097397.name: Coefficients in asymptotic expansion of normal probability function.

A097398.name: Matrix T(m,x(1)), m>=1, x(1)>=2, read by antidiagonals, where T(m,x(1)) gives the position of the first noninteger term in the sequence defined by x(n)=(x(n-1)*(x(n-1)^m+n-1))/n for n>=2 with exponent m and the given starting value x(1).

A097399.name: Maximum of the determinant over all permutations of the entries of a 3 X 3 matrix which are consecutive integers in the range (n-4,n+4).
formula: G.f.: (x^13+12*x^3+50*x^2-68*x+86) / (x-1)^2. [_Colin Barker_, Dec 13 2012] [I suspect this is merely a conjecture. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jun 09 2018]

A097400.name: Number of different values that can be assumed by the determinant of a 3 X 3 matrix whose elements are all permutations of the consecutive integers in the range (n-4,n+4).

A097401.name: Largest achievable determinant of a 3 X 3 matrix whose elements are 9 distinct nonnegative integers chosen from the range 0..n.
formula: An optimal choice and arrangement is of the following form: det((n, n-5, 1), (2, n-1, n-3), (n-4, 0, n-2)) = 2*(n^3 - 9*n^2 + 34*n - 42). There are 35 other equivalent arrangements corresponding to permutations of rows and columns.

A097402.name: Numbers n such that 6*10^n + 2*R_n + 5 is prime, where R_n = 11...1 is the repunit (A002275) of length n.

A097403.name: Minimum wind speed in knots for Beaufort Number n.

A097404.name: Minimum wind speed in statute miles per hour for Beaufort Number n.

A097405.name: Number of different rectangles created when a square sheet of paper is folded n times, the first time by one of the diagonals of the square and after by the median of the triangle.
formula: Let p(x) = x^2 (x+1)^2/4 and d(x) = (x^4 - x^2 - 6 x)/24. Then, for n>1, a(n) = -1 + p(2^ceiling(n/2-1)) + d(2^floor(n/2))

A097406.name: Largest primitive prime factor of 2^n-1, or a(n) = 1 if no such prime exists.

A097415.name: Values of k such that the first digit of 2^k is 9.

A097416.name: Numbers n such that A076078(m)=n for some m, excluding powers of 2.

A097417.name: a(1)=1; a(n+1) = Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) a(floor(n/k)).
formula: Ratio a(n+1)/a(n) seems to tend to 1 + Golden Ratio = 2.61803398... = 1 + A001622. - Mark Hudson (mrmarkhudson(AT)hotmail.com), Aug 23 2004

Satisfies the "partial linear recursion": a(prime(n)+1) = 3*a(prime(n))- a(prime(n)-1). This explains why we get a(n+1)/a(n) -> 1 + phi. Also, lim_{n->infty} a(n)/(1 + phi)^n exists but should not have a simple closed form. - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 29 2004

A097418.name: Triangle of coefficients of a certain sequence of polynomials f_n(x) arising in connection with deformations of coordinate rings of type D Kleinian singularities.

A097420.name: Height of n-th (rational) multiple nP of point P(3,5) on the cubic curve y^2=x^3 - 2.

A097422.name: Sum{k=1 to n} H(k) k!, where H(k) = sum{j=1 to k} 1/j.

A097423.name: Numerator of Product_{k=1..n} H(k), where H(k) = Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j, the k-th harmonic number.

A097424.name: Denominator of Product_{k=1..n} H(k), where H(k) = Sum_{j=1..k} 1/j, the k-th harmonic number.

A097425.name: a(1) = 500, then a(n) is the concatenation of the roman numerals (I, V, X, L, C, D, M) visible in a(n-1) written in English.

A097426.name: Integer part of the circumference of circles with prime diameters.

A097427.name: Integer part of the area of circles with prime radii.

A097428.name: Integer part of the diameters of circles with prime circumferences.

A097429.name: Integer part of the radii of circles with prime areas.

A097430.name: Integer part of the radii of circles with area n.

A097431.name: Integer part of the hypotenuse of right triangles with consecutive prime legs.

A097432.name: Integer part of the hypotenuse of right triangles with consecutive integer legs.

A097433.name: Integer part of the hypotenuse of prime leg isosceles right triangles.
formula: a(n) = floor( sqrt(2*p(n)^2)), where p(n) = n-th prime. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Feb 23 2015

A097434.name: Value of C in y = x^2 + 5x + C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 3.

A097435.name: Numbers n such that n and its reversal are distinct brilliant numbers (A078972).

A097436.name: Value of C in y = x^2+7x+C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 4.

A097437.name: Value of C in y = x^2 + 9x + C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 5.

A097439.name: Least k such that k*P(n)#/3 - 3 and k*P(n)#/3 + 3 are consecutive primes P(i)= i-th prime, P(i)# = i-th primorial.

A097440.name: Least k such that k*P(n)#/2 - 2 and k*P(n)#/2 + 4 are consecutive primes P(i)= i-th prime, P(i)# = i-th primorial.

A097441.name: Least k such that k*P(n)#/2 - 4 and k*P(n)#/2 + 2 are consecutive primes P(i)= i-th prime, P(i)# = i-th primorial.

A097442.name: Integer part of the area of consecutive prime sided isosceles triangles.
formula: Consider prime isosceles triangles of sides (2, 3, 3), (3, 5, 5), ..., (x, y, y) where x is prime and y is the next prime after x. Then area = 1/2*x*sqrt(y^2-(x/2)^2). Output floor(area)

A097443.name: Half-period primes, i.e., primes p for which the decimal expansion of 1/p has period (p-1)/2.

A097444.name: Second occurrence where n# + p is prime for primes p = 3,5,...
formula: n# is n primorial = product of primes 2*3*5*...*p<=n

A097445.name: Second occurrence where n# - p is prime for primes p = 3,5,...
formula: n# is n primorial = product of primes 2*3*5*...*p<=n

A097446.name: Concatenate consecutive prime-sided isosceles triangles.
formula: Consider triangles with sides (2, 3, 3), (3, 5, 5), .., (x, y, y) where x is prime and y is the next prime after x. Concatenate these sides for output.

A097447.name: Primes in the concatenation of consecutive prime-sided isosceles triangles.
formula: Consider triangles with sides (2, 3, 3), (3, 5, 5), .., (x, y, y) where x is prime and y is the next prime after x. Concatenate these sides and output if prime.

A097448.name: If n is square, replace with sqrt(n).

A097449.name: If n is a cube, replace it with the cube root of n.

A097450.name: If n is square, replace with the sqrt(n)-th prime.

A097451.name: Number of partitions of n into parts congruent to {2, 3, 4} mod 6.
formula: Expansion of psi(x^3) / f(-x^2) in powers of x where psi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 24 2013
Expansion of q^(-7/24) * eta(q^6)^2 / (eta(q^2) * eta(q^3) in powers of q. - _Michael Somos_, Sep 24 2013
Expansion of f(-x, -x^5) / f(-x, -x^2) in powers of x where f(, ) is Ramanujan's general theta function. - _Michael Somos_, Oct 06 2015

A097452.name: Primes of the form prime(k) + nonprime(k) for some k.

A097453.name: Primes p of the form p = prime(k) - composite(k) for some k.

A097454.name: a(n) = (number of nonprimes <= n) - (number of primes <= n).
formula: a(n) = n - 2*pi(n) =  n - 2*A000720(n). - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Jun 16 2013
a(n) - a(n-1) = 1 - 2*A010051(n) for n > 1. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Dec 18 2018

A097456.name: Integer part of the ratio (number of composites <=n) / (number of primes <=n).
formula: pi(n) = number of primes <= n. Ratio = (n - pi(n))/pi(n) = n/pi(n) - 1. Output floor(Ratio)

A097457.name: If n is prime replace with the n-th nonprime otherwise replace with the n-th prime.

A097458.name: The value of C in y = x^2+11x+C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 6.

A097459.name: The value of C in y = x^2+13x+C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 7.

A097460.name: The value of C in y = x^2+15x+C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 8.

A097461.name: The value of C in y = x^2+17x+C such that y is prime for all x = 0 to 9.

A097462.name: Multiplication table for numbers 0 through 10 read by rows.

A097463.name: Let P(i) = i-th prime. To get a(n), factor P(n)-1 as a product of primes, then concatenate the exponents.

A097465.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1, a(n) = smallest positive integer which is not among earlier terms of sequence, is coprime to a(n-1) and is not equal to a(n-1) +- 1.

A097466.name: Number of primes in each interval of one hundred numbers starting at 10000000.

A097467.name: Permutation of natural numbers inverse to A097465.

A097468.name: Number of 1's in the decimal expansion of the lesser of twin primes.

A097469.name: Decimal expansion of growth constant C for dimer model on square grid.
formula: Equals e^(G/Pi), with G = A006752 (Catalan's constant).
Equals exp((1/Pi^2) * Integral_{x=0..Pi/2, y=0..Pi/2} log(4*cos(x)^2 + 4*cos(y)^2) dx dy). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Jan 04 2021

A097470.name: Number of 0's in the decimal expansion of the lesser of twin primes.

A097472.name: Number of different candle trees having a total of m edges.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{s, d, k>=0 with s+d+k=m} binomial(s+2d+1, s)*binomial(s, k);
a(n) = 1 + Sum_{m=1..n} Sum_{k=1..n-m+1} binomial(k, n-m-k+1)*binomial(k+2*m-1,2*m-1). - _Vladimir Kruchinin_, May 12 2011

A097473.name: Slowest ever increasing sequence in which all successive digits are the digits of the Fibonacci sequence.
formula: Write down the Fibonacci sequence and consider it as a unique succession of digits. Divide up into chunks of minimal length (and not beginning with 0) so that chunks are increasing numbers in order to form the slowest ever increasing sequences of slices (disregarding the number of digits) of the succession of the digits of the Fibonacci sequence.

A097474.name: Triangle T(n,k) read by rows: see formula lines for definition.
formula: 2^-floor((n+2)/2)*T(n+1, k) = binomial(2n+3, 2k) - Sum_{j=k..n} binomial(2n+3, 2j+1)*2^-floor((j+3)/2)*T(j, k), k=0..n.

A097475.name: Numbers n such that n^12 - n^6 + 1 is prime.

A097477.name: a(n) = number of earlier terms greater than a(floor(n/2)); a(1)=1.

A097478.name: Atomic numbers of halogens in the periodic table.

A097479.name: Weight distribution of [127,50,27] primitive binary BCH code.

A097480.name: Positive integers n such that 2n-15 is prime.
formula: Half of p+15 where p is a prime greater than 2.

A097481.name: Write the positive even integers on labels in numerical order, forming an infinite sequence L. Consider the succession of digits of L: 2 4 6 8 1 0 1 2 1 4 1 6 1 8 2 0 2 2 2 4 2 6 2 8 3 0 ... (A036211). This sequence gives a derangement of L that produces the same succession of digits, subject to the constraint that the smallest unused label must be used that does not lead to a contradiction.

A097483.name: Number of Gorenstein Schubert varieties in the (type A) flag variety Flags(C^n).

A097484.name: Write the odd positive integers on labels in numerical order, forming an infinite sequence L. Consider the succession of single digits of L: 1 3 5 7 9 1 1 1 3 1 5 1 7 1 9 2 1 2 3 2 5 2 7 2 9 3 1 ... (A031312). This sequence is a derangement of L that produces the same succession of digits, subject to the constraint that the smallest unused label must be used that does not lead to a contradiction.

A097485.name: Write the positive integers on labels in numerical order, forming an infinite sequence L. The e.g.f. of this Appell sequence of polynomials P(n,x) is e^(xt) times the e.g.f. AC(t) of the aerated Catalan numbers A126120. AC(t) = I_1(2t)/t, where I_n(x) = T_n(d/dx) I_0(x) are the modified Bessel functions of the first kind and T_n, the Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.

P(n,x) has the lowering and raising operators L = d/dx = D and R = d/dD log{M(x,D)} = x + d/dD log{AC(D)} = x + Sum_{n>=0} c(n) D^(2n+1)/(2n+1)! with c(n) = (-1)^n A180874(n+1), i.e., L P(n,x) = n P(n-1,x) and R P(n,x) = P(n+1,x).
(P(.,x) + y)^n = P(n,x+y) = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k) P(k,x) y^(n-k) = (b.+x+y)^n, where (b.)^k = b_k = A126120(k).
Exp(b.D) e^(xt) = exp[(x+b.)t] = exp[P(.,x)t] = e^(b.t) e^(xt) = e^(xt) AC(t).
See p. 12 of the Alexeev et al. link and A055151 for a refinement.

Shifted o.g.f: G(x,t) = [1-tx-sqrt[(1-tx)^2-4x^2]] / 2x = x + t x^2 + (1+t) x^3 + ... has the compositional inverse Ginv(x,t) = x / [1 + tx + x^2] = x - t x^2 +(-1+t^2) x^3 + (2t-t^3) x^4 + (1-3t^2+t^4) x^5 + ..., a shifted o.g.f. for the signed Chebyshev polynomials of the second kind of A049310 (cf. also the Fibonacci polynomials of A011973). Then the inversion formula of A134264, involving non-crossing partitions and free probability with their multitude of interpretations (cf. A125181 also), can be used with h_0 = 1, h_1 = t, and h_2 = 1 to interpret the coefficients of the Motzkin polynomials combinatorially.
Provides coefficients of the inverse of f(x) = x / [1 + h1 x + h2 x^2], a bivariate generating function of A049310 (mod signs).
finv(x) = [(1-h1*x) - sqrt[(1-h1*x)^2-4h2*x^2]]/(2*h2*x) = x + h1 x^2 + (h2 + h1^2) x^3 + (3 h1 h2 + h1^3) x^4 + ... is a bivariate o.g.f. for this entry.

The infinitesimal generator for finv(x) is g(x) d/dx with g(x) = 1 /[df(x)/dx] = x^2 / [(f(x))^2 (1- h2 x^2)] = (1 + h1 x + h2 x^2)^2 / (1 - h2 x^2) so that [g(x)d/dx]^n/n! x evaluated at x = 0 gives the row polynomials FI(n,h1,h2) of the compositional inverse of f(x), i.e., exp[x g(u)d/du] u |_(u=0) = finv(x) = 1 /[1 -x FI(.,h1,h2)]. Cf. A145271. E.g.,

And with D = d/dh1, FI(n+1, h1,h2) = MT(n,h1,h2) = (b.y + h1)^n = Sum_{k=0..n} binomial(n,k) b(k) y^k h1^(n-k) = exp[(b.y D] (h1)^n = AC(y D) (h1)^n, where b(k) = A126120(k), y = sqrt(h2), and AC(t) is defined in my Jan 23 formulas above. Equivalently, AC(y D) e^(x h1) = exp[x MT(.,h1,h2)].

The MT polynomials comprise an Appell sequence in h1 with e.g.f. e^(h1*x) AC(xy) = exp[x MT(.,h1,h2)] with lowering operator L = d/dh1 = D, i.e., L MT(n,h1,h2) = dMT(n,h1,h2)/dh1 = n MT(n-1,h1,h2) and raising operator R = h1 + dlog{AC(y L)}/dL = h1 + Sum_{n>=0} c(n) h2^(n+1) D^(2n+1)/(2n+1)! = h1 + h2 d/dh1 - h2^2 (d/dh1)^3/3! + 5 h2^3 (d/dh1)^5/5! - ...  with c(n) = (-1)^n A180874(n+1) (consistent with the raising operator in the Jan 23 formulas).
The compositional inverse finv(x) is also obtained from the non-crossing partitions of A134264 (or A125181) with h_0 = 1, h_1 = h1, h_2 = h2, and h_n = 0 for all other n.
See A238390 for the umbral compositional inverse in h1 of MT(n,h1,h2) and inverse matrix.

z1(x,h1,h2) = finv(x), the bivariate o.g.f. above for this entry, is the zero that vanishes for x=0 for the quadratic polynomial Q(z;z1(x,h1,h2),z2(x,h1,h2)) = (z-z1)(z-z2) = z^2 - (z1+z2) z + (z1*z2) = z^2 - e1 z + e2 = z^2 - [(1-h1*x)/(h2*x)] z + 1/h2, where e1 and e2 are the elementary symmetric polynomials for two indeterminates.
The other zero is given by z2(x,h1,h2) = (1 - h1*x)/(h2*x) - z1(x,h1,h2) = [1 - h1*x + sqrt[(1-h1*x)^2 - 4 h2*x^2]] / (2h2*x).

A097613.name: a(n) = binomial(2n-3,n-1) + binomial(2n-2,n-2).

W_c(0)=-infinity, W_c(1)=0 and W_c(4)=infinity. For 0<x<1, W_c(x)<0, and for 1<x<4, W_c(x)>0. - _Karol A. Penson_, Aug 05 2013

For n>18 up to the limit investigated (n<=26) one choice maximizing the determinant is det((n, 6, 2, n-8), (3, n-1, 4, n-5), (n-7, n-6, n-3, 0), (5, 1, n-2, n-4))= 3*n^4-60*n^3+491*n^2-1821*n+2624. In both cases there are 575 other equivalent arrangements corresponding to permutations of rows and columns.

A097695.name: Largest achievable determinant of a 4 X 4 matrix whose elements are 16 distinct integers chosen from the range -n...n.

A097877.name: Triangle read by rows: T(n,k) is the number of Dyck n-paths with k large components, 0 <= k <= n/2.
formula: G.f.: 2/(1 + t*(1 - 4*z)^(1/2) + (1 - 2*z)(1-t)) = Sum_{n>=0, k>=0} T(n, k) z^n t^k satisfies (1-z)*G = 1 + z*t*(CatalanGF[z]-1)*G. The gf for Dyck paths (A000108) with z marking semilength is CatalanGF[z]:=(1 - sqrt[1 - 4*z])/(2*z). Hence the gf for prime Dyck paths is z*CatalanGF[z] and the gf for non-UD prime Dyck paths is S(z):= z*CatalanGF[z]-z. For fixed k, the gf for (T(n, k))_{n>=0} is S(z)^k/(1-z)^(k+1). This is clear because 1/(1-z) is the gf for all-UD Dyck paths (including the empty one) and a Dyck path with k large components is a product (uniquely) of an all-UD, a non-UD prime, an all-UD, a non-UD prime, ... with k non-UD primes and k+1 all-UDs.
